==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trio
<hw>Tri"o</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It., fr. L.
<ets>tres</ets>, <ets>tria</ets>, three: cf. F. <ets>trio</ets>, from
the Italian. See <er>Three</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Three,
considered collectively; three in company or acting together; a set of
three; three united.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>trio</qex> were well accustomed to act together, and were
linked to each other by ties of mutual interest.</q>
<rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A composition for
three parts or three instruments.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The secondary,
or episodical, movement of a minuet or scherzo, as in a sonata or
symphony, or of a march, or of various dance forms; -- not limited to
three parts or instruments.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Triobolary</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Triobolar</ent>⟦br⟧
